b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n\n<workbook_page id="p3_gas_density" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Gas Density and Molar Mass </title>\n        <objref idref="stoich_gas2"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n        <p>One important application of the ideal gas law is to determine its molar mass and thereby\n            assist in its identification using the measured density of the gas. Review the\n            interactive below to see the derivation of the formula used to calculate the molar mass\n            of a gas from its density. </p>\n        \n     <!--   <section>\n            <title>Slide Show</title>\n            <body><iframe src="https://h5p.org/h5p/embed/225014" width="750" height="440"></iframe></body>\n        </section>-->\n        \n        <section>\n            <title>Slide Show</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>Press "NEXT" to advance slide show.</p>\n                <wb:inline idref="density_mm_ss"></wb:inline>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        <dl>\n            <dt><em>Molar Mass of a Gas</em> </dt>\n            <dd>\n       \n        <p>The molar mass of a gas can be determined given its density, temperature, and pressure\n            with the following equation: </p>\n        <p><formula>$$\\require{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = \\frac{dRT}{P}$$</formula></p>\n        <p>Where <em style="italic">d</em> = density, <em style="italic">R</em> = ideal gas law\n            constant, <em style="italic">T</em> = temperature, and <em style="italic">P</em> = pressure.</p></dd>\n        </dl>\n      <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n\n        <example>\n            <p>A gas was found to have a density of 0.0847 g/L at 17.0 \xc2\xb0C and a pressure of 760\n                torr. What is its molar mass? What is the gas?</p>\n            <p><formula>$$\\require{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = \\frac{dRT}{P}$$</formula></p>\n            <p>As before when using the ideal gas law constant, we need to ensure that the units in\n                the constant match the units used for the other variables and as before when using\n                the ideal gas law equation temperature must be in K. First we will convert the\n                pressure to units of atm. You will recall that 760 torr = 1 atm.</p>\n            <p><formula>$$\\require{cancel} \\require{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = \\frac{(0.0847\n                    \\mathrm{g/}\\cancel{\\mathrm{L}})( 0.08206 \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}}\\\n                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{L}}\\ \\mathrm{mol^{-1}}\\ \\cancel{\\mathrm{K^{-1}}})(290\n                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{K}})}{1 \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}}}$$</formula></p>\n            <p><formula>$$\\require{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = 2.02 \\mathrm{g/mol}$$</formula></p>\n            <p>The gas is hydrogen, H<sub>2</sub>.</p>\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="densitymm_lbde7fc969d89b54378a7a084171d558c54" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n        <wb:inline idref="densitymm_digt1beb0d5347ddc4101870002f409a16d57" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>       \n              <p>This equation can also be used to determine the density of a known gas at a given\n            temperature and pressure. </p>\n        <example>\n            <p>Calculate the density of chlorine gas (Cl<sub>2</sub>) at 22 <sup>o</sup>C and 735 torr.</p>\n            <p>We can use the molar mass of a gas equation, </p>\n            <p><formula>$$\\require{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = \\frac{dRT}{P}$$</formula></p>\n            <p>rearranging it to solve for density. </p>\n            <p><formula>$$\\require{mathrsfs} d = \\frac{\\mathscr{M}P}{RT}$$</formula></p>\n            <p>Because we know the identity of the gas, we can easily calculate its molar mass and\n                substitute it and the other given values (making the necessary conversions) into the\n                equation. </p>\n            <p><formula>$$\\require{cancel} d = \\frac{(70.90 \\mathrm{g/}\\\n                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}})(0.967 \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}})}{ (0.08206\n                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}}\\ \\mathrm{L} \\cancel{\\mathrm{mol^{-1}}}\\\n                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{K^{-1}}})(295 \\cancel{\\mathrm{K}})} = 2.83\n                    \\mathrm{g/L}$$</formula></p>\n\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="densitymm_digt2fe87000d740a4450ada032b471ce9c3e" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\n\n\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="http://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n                >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">Creative Commons Attribution 4.0\n                License</link>. </p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n                href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312."\n                >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'